gs.name: gs
gs.description:
A storage for different kind of game variables. The following scopes for variables exist:

- Local Variables -> Only valid for the current scene. - Global Variables -> Valid for the whole game but bound to a single save-game. - Persistent Variables -> Valid for the whole game indepentent from the save-games.

The following data-types exist:

- Strings -> Variables storing text data. - Numbers -> Variables storing integer number values. - Booleans -> Variables storing boolean values. (Called "Switches" for easier understanding) - Lists -> Variables storing multiple other variables. Lists can also contain Lists.

Local variables are stored by scene UID. For each scene UID a list of local variables is stored.

Global and persistent variables are stored and a specific domain. A domain is just a unique name such as com.example.game for example. The default domain is an empty string. Domains are useful to avoid overlapping of variable numbers when sharing content with other users.

ui.name: ui
ui.description: An ui point is like a regular point with an x- and y-coordinate but if one of the coordinates is changed the needsUpdate property of the assigned game object will be set to true to trigger a refresh.

params.name: params
params.description: - The params-object containing the data-grid settings.

vn.name: vn
vn.description:
A scene object manages a whole visual novel scene with backgrounds, characters,
messages, etc.

AudioManager.name: AudioManager
AudioManager.description: Manages the audio playback of the game.

CircularDistortionEffect.name: CircularDistortionEffect
CircularDistortionEffect.description:
An effect collection stores all effects by name. So if you add custom effects, you
have to create an own class and inherit from gs.EffectCollection and add your
own effects in the constructor. It is important to put the super-call at the end and not
at the beginning.

CommandFieldFlags.name: CommandFieldFlags
CommandFieldFlags.description: An enumeration of command field flags.

Component_ActionHandler.name: Component_ActionHandler
Component_ActionHandler.description:
An action-handler component allows a UI game object to execute
actions. An action can be a method-call of a component or of the scene which
always takes two parameters: Sender and Params. For more info about
UI actions, see help-file.

Component_AnimationExecutor.name: Component_AnimationExecutor
Component_AnimationExecutor.description:
An animation-handler component allows a UI game object to execute
a flow of animations. For more information about UI animations, see help-file.

Component_AnimationHandler.name: Component_AnimationHandler
Component_AnimationHandler.description:
An animation-handler component allows a UI game object to execute
a flow of animations. For more information about UI animations, see help-file.

Component_Animation.name: Component_Animation
Component_Animation.description:
The base-class of all animation components. An animation-component executes a certain animation on a game object. The type of the animation depends on the component.

In regular, animation components a used together with the gs.Component_Animator component.

Component_Animator.name: Component_Animator
Component_Animator.description:
An animator-component allows to execute different kind of animations 
on a game object. The animations are using the game object's 
dstRect & offset-property to execute.

Component.name: Component
Component.description:
The base class of all components. A component defines a certain piece of
game logic.

Component_BindingHandler.name: Component_BindingHandler
Component_BindingHandler.description:
A binding-handler component allows a UI game object to execute property-bindings.

For example: A text-label can bind its text-property to a backend-field like the current music-volume to always display correct music-volume. If the volume changes, the text-property will be updated automatically. To define a binding, a special property-path syntax is used. For example:

$myTextField.text

is a property-path to access the text-property of a text-field object with the identifier "myTextField". For more information, take a look into the "In Game UI System" section of the help-file.

Component_BlendAnimation.name: Component_BlendAnimation
Component_BlendAnimation.description: Executes a blend-animation on a game-object.

Component_BlurAnimation.name: Component_BlurAnimation
Component_BlurAnimation.description: Executes a blur-animation on a game-object.

Component_CallSceneInterpreter.name: Component_CallSceneInterpreter
Component_CallSceneInterpreter.description:
A command interpreter used as a sub-interpreter to execute CallScene commands. See
gs.Component_CommandInterpreter for more information.

Component_CharacterBehavior.name: Component_CharacterBehavior
Component_CharacterBehavior.description:
A behavior-component which handles the character-specific behavior like
talking and idle.

Component_MoveAnimation.name: Component_MoveAnimation
Component_MoveAnimation.description: Executes a move-animation on a game-object.

LivePreviewInfo.name: LivePreviewInfo
LivePreviewInfo.description: Stores internal preview-info if the game runs currently in Live-Preview.

InterpreterContext.name: InterpreterContext
InterpreterContext.description:
Describes an interpreter-context which holds information about
the interpreter's owner and also unique ID used for accessing correct
local variables.

Component_CommandInterpreter.name: Component_CommandInterpreter
Component_CommandInterpreter.description:
A component which allows a game object to process commands like for
scene-objects. For each command a command-function exists. To add
own custom commands to the interpreter just create a sub-class and
override the gs.Component_CommandInterpreter.assignCommand method
and assign the command-function for your custom-command.

Component_CommonEventBehavior.name: Component_CommonEventBehavior
Component_CommonEventBehavior.description: A component which allows a game object to execute common-events.

Component_Container.name: Component_Container
Component_Container.description: A container component allows an object to have sub-objects.

Component_DataGridBehavior.name: Component_DataGridBehavior
Component_DataGridBehavior.description:
The data-grid behavior component defines the logic for a data-grid. A data-grid
allows to display items from a associated data-source using a specified
item-template. Unlike a stack-layout, a data-grid is optimized to display even high amounts of items but they all
need to use the same item-template with same size.

Component_DomainContainer.name: Component_DomainContainer
Component_DomainContainer.description: A container component allows an object to have sub-objects.

Component_Draggable.name: Component_Draggable
Component_Draggable.description:
Makes a game object draggable using mouse/touch. The dragging can be
vertical, horizontal or both. It can be configured as pixel-wise or 
step-wise dragging. For example: To create a slider for UI with
fixed steps, step-wise is useful while a pixel-wise dragging could
be used for a volume-slider.

Component_EventEmitter.name: Component_EventEmitter
Component_EventEmitter.description:
A component which allow a game object to fire events and manage a list
of observers.

Component_FieldAnimation.name: Component_FieldAnimation
Component_FieldAnimation.description:
Executes a field-animation. A field-animation animates a certain
property of the game-object as long as it is a number-property.

Component_FrameAnimation.name: Component_FrameAnimation
Component_FrameAnimation.description: Executes a classic image-frame animation defined in Database. The image in regular contains multiple sub-images (frames) which are then animated by modifying the srcRect property of the game object.

Component_Frame.name: Component_Frame
Component_Frame.description:
A frame constructs a graphical frame from its skin-image. The frame can
rendered by tiling or strechting the four sides of the frame. A frame
is useful for creating In-Game UI windows and boxes. For more info about 
the skin-image format, see help-file.

Component_FreeLayoutBehavior.name: Component_FreeLayoutBehavior
Component_FreeLayoutBehavior.description:
Turns a game object into a free-layout and layouts all sub-objects at their specified positions. So that kind of layout allows each sub-object to be freely positioned.
In addition, each sub-object can have different alignment options.

Component_GameSceneBehavior.name: Component_GameSceneBehavior
Component_GameSceneBehavior.description: Defines the behavior of visual novel game scene.

Component_GridLayoutBehavior.name: Component_GridLayoutBehavior
Component_GridLayoutBehavior.description:
Turns a game object into a free-layout and layouts all sub-objects
in a grid of rows and columns.

Component_Handler.name: Component_Handler
Component_Handler.description:
The base class for all handler-components. A handler-component is
used to handle condition- or event-based processes of a In-Game UI
object like executing bindings or triggering actions.

A handler is only executed if all assigned conditions and events are
true.

Component_HotspotBehavior.name: Component_HotspotBehavior
Component_HotspotBehavior.description:
Adds a hotspot-behavior to a game object. That allows a game object
to respond to mouse/touch actions by firing an action-event or changing
the game object's image.

Component_ImageMap.name: Component_ImageMap
Component_ImageMap.description: A component which turns a game object into an interactive image-map.

Component_InputHandler.name: Component_InputHandler
Component_InputHandler.description:
The input-handler component is an interface between the input-system
of the basic-engine and the game's event-system. In regular this
component is used only by game scene to allow its game objects to
receive input-events.

Those input-events are necessary to solve the problem which game-object
responds to a user-action first by building a responder-chain.

Component_IntervalTimer.name: Component_IntervalTimer
Component_IntervalTimer.description:
A component which adds timing-features to a game object. The game object
will send an "elapsed" event everytime the time interval has been elapsed.

Component_LayoutBehavior.name: Component_LayoutBehavior
Component_LayoutBehavior.description:
The base class of all layout-components. A layout-component is used to layout assigned sub-objects in a specific way depending on the layout-type. For example: A grid-layout layouts its sub-objects like a grid using rows and columns. The game object needs a container-component.

A layout can also be configured as scrollable. In that case, layout's content can be larger than the layout-bounds and is automatically clipped. The content can be scrolled using mouse-wheel or touch-gesture.

Component_LayoutSceneBehavior.name: Component_LayoutSceneBehavior
Component_LayoutSceneBehavior.description:
The base class of all scene-behavior components. A scene-behavior component
define the logic of a single game scene.

Component_Live2DAnimation.name: Component_Live2DAnimation
Component_Live2DAnimation.description: Executes an animation on specific Live2D model-parameter of the Live2D  game-object.

Component_Live2D.name: Component_Live2D
Component_Live2D.description:
A Live2D component which allows a game-object to become a animated
Live2D character.

Component_MaskAnimation.name: Component_MaskAnimation
Component_MaskAnimation.description: Executes a mask-animation on a game-object.

Component_MessageBehavior.name: Component_MessageBehavior
Component_MessageBehavior.description: A behavior-component to define the behavior of a game-message.

Component_MessageTextRenderer.name: Component_MessageTextRenderer
Component_MessageTextRenderer.description:
A text-renderer component to render an animated and interactive message text using
dimensions of the game object's destination-rectangle. The message is displayed
using a sprite for each line instead of drawing to the game object's bitmap object.

Component_NumberInput.name: Component_NumberInput
Component_NumberInput.description:
The number-input component defines the logic for the number-input window
of the default In-Game UI.

Component_PanelBehavior.name: Component_PanelBehavior
Component_PanelBehavior.description:
A panel-component gives a game-object the same capabilities like a visual object but has no graphical representation. So a panel has a position and a size.

It can be used to make invisible hotspot-areas or modal-blocking areas for example.

Component_PathAnimation.name: Component_PathAnimation
Component_PathAnimation.description:
Executes a path-animation on a game-object. A path-animation moves the
game-object along a path of quadratic bezier-curves.

Component_PixelateAnimation.name: Component_PixelateAnimation
Component_PixelateAnimation.description: Executes a pixelate-animation on a game-object.

Component_Quad.name: Component_Quad
Component_Quad.description:
A quad component displays rectangle on the screen using the color
of the game object.

Component_RotateAnimation.name: Component_RotateAnimation
Component_RotateAnimation.description: Executes a rotate-animation on a game-object.

Component_SceneBehavior.name: Component_SceneBehavior
Component_SceneBehavior.description:
The base class of all scene-behavior components. A scene-behavior component
define the logic of a single game scene.

Component_ShakeAnimation.name: Component_ShakeAnimation
Component_ShakeAnimation.description: Executes a horizontal shake-animation on a game-object.

Component_SpreadLayoutBehavior.name: Component_SpreadLayoutBehavior
Component_SpreadLayoutBehavior.description:
Turns a game object into a spread-layout and spreads all sub-objects
evenly over the layout-space vertically or horizontally. The game object needs a 
container-component.

Component_Sprite.name: Component_Sprite
Component_Sprite.description:
A sprite component to display an object on screen. It can be managed or
unmanaged. A managed sprite is automatically added to the graphics-system
and rendered every frame until it gets disposed. An unmanaged sprite needs
to be added and removed manually.

Component_StackLayoutBehavior.name: Component_StackLayoutBehavior
Component_StackLayoutBehavior.description:
Turns a game object into a stack-layout and layouts all sub-objects like stack vertically or horizontally. The game object needs a container-component.
The sub-objects in a stack-layout can be configured as resizable or non-resizable(fixed-size). For example:

Lets say we have a layout-size of 500px in width with three controls.

| 80px | dynamic | 80px |

Two controls have a fixed size of 80px and the middle-control has a dynamic-size because it is configured to be resizable. In that case, the size of the resizable control would be 340px because that is the free space left after subtracting the size(160px) of the fixed-size controls.

In addition, each sub-object can have different alignment options.

Component_TextInput.name: Component_TextInput
Component_TextInput.description:
The text-input component defines the logic for the text-input window
of the default In-Game UI.

Component_TextRenderer.name: Component_TextRenderer
Component_TextRenderer.description:
A text-renderer component allow to draw plain or formatted text on a game object's bitmap. For formatted text, different text-codes can be used to add formatting or define a placeholder.

A text-code uses the following syntax:

{code:value} <- Single Value
{code:value1,value2,...} <- Multiple Values

Example:

"This is {Y:I}a Text{Y:N}" <- "a Text" will be italic here.
"The value is {GN:1}" <- "{GN:1}" will be replaced for the value of the global number variable 0001.

For a list of all available text-codes with examples, just take a look into the offical help-file.

Component_ThreePartImage.name: Component_ThreePartImage
Component_ThreePartImage.description:
A three-part image component displays an object on screen using three sub-images: start, middle and end. The start and end will be rendered with fixed size while the middle-part will be stretched in a way like this:

|Start-Part Fixed|<-----------Middle-Part Stretched----------->|End-Part Fixed

A three-part image is automatically added to the graphics-system and rendered every frame until it gets disposed. It can be horizontal or vertical.

Component_TilingPlane.name: Component_TilingPlane
Component_TilingPlane.description:
A tiling plane component tiles the image of the game object endless over the screen. The
tiling can be vertical, horizontal or both. The sprite can be managed or
unmanaged. A managed sprite is automatically added to the graphics-system
and processed every frame until it gets disposed. An unmanaged sprite needs
to be added and removed manually.

Component_TilingSprite.name: Component_TilingSprite
Component_TilingSprite.description:
A tiling sprite component tiles the image of the game object on screen. The
tiling can be vertical, horizontal or both. The sprite can be managed or
unmanaged. A managed sprite is automatically added to the graphics-system
and processed every frame until it gets disposed. An unmanaged sprite needs
to be added and removed manually.

Component_Timer.name: Component_Timer
Component_Timer.description:
A component which adds timing-features to a game object. A timer-component
can be used as a regular timer or as a stop-watch.

Component_TintAnimation.name: Component_TintAnimation
Component_TintAnimation.description:
Executes a tint-animation on a game-object. The tint is executed on
the game object's tone-property.

Component_Viewport.name: Component_Viewport
Component_Viewport.description:
A viewport component can contain multiple graphic objects and will automatically 
clip them if they move out of the viewport-rectangle. The area of a viewport
can also be tinted or colored. So to tint the whole for example, it enough
to create a viewport taking the whole screen-space and then setting the
tone or color property.

Component_Visual.name: Component_Visual
Component_Visual.description: The base class for all components displaying an object on screen.

Component_WebStartBehavior.name: Component_WebStartBehavior
Component_WebStartBehavior.description:
The web-start scene is used if the game has been loaded via mobile webbrowser. That web-start
scene lets the player tap on the screen to start the actual game which is necessary to make
audio-playback working because of browser-security.

Component_WobbleAnimation.name: Component_WobbleAnimation
Component_WobbleAnimation.description: Executes a blur-animation on a game-object.

Component_ZoomAnimation.name: Component_ZoomAnimation
Component_ZoomAnimation.description: Executes a zoom-animation on a game-object.

Helper.name: Helper
Helper.description:
A helper class containing helper-functions like generating letter-descriptors
from database defined text-input pages.

ContainerDisposeBehavior.name: ContainerDisposeBehavior
ContainerDisposeBehavior.description:
An enumeration of different dispose behaviors for containers. A dispose
behavior describes what should happen with objects in a container after
they got disposed.

DataManager.name: DataManager
DataManager.description:
Manages the game's data like loading documents. Documents are stored in the data folder of the game in JSON format. The UID is used as the file-name. A document has the following structure:

UID - Unique Identifier
Items -> An object containing all the items/fields of the document.
Items.Type -> The type of the document
Items.Name -> The name of the document

DataOptimizer.name: DataOptimizer
DataOptimizer.description:
The data optimizer is to optimize data structures coming from data files to
make processing faster. One way of optimization for example is to convert
regular array to typed arrays.

Easing.name: Easing
Easing.description:
The Easing class provides different types of animation using different easings. The easing
of an animation controls how hard/soft the animation starts and/or stops.

Easings.name: Easings
Easings.description: Holds different easing types and helper methods.

GameManager.name: GameManager
GameManager.description:
Manages all general things around the game like holding the game settings,
manages the save/load of a game, etc.

GameTemp.name: GameTemp
GameTemp.description:
The GameTemp holds the temporary data of the currently running game like currently displayed
choices, choice timer, etc. The GameTemp is written to the save-game as well.

ImageHandling.name: ImageHandling
ImageHandling.description: Enumeration describing the different types of image-handling.

LanguageManager.name: LanguageManager
LanguageManager.description: Manages the different languages of the game.

LayoutManagementMode.name: LayoutManagementMode
LayoutManagementMode.description:
An enumeration of different management modes describing how a layout should
handle its sub-objects coming from a data-source.

Main.name: Main
Main.description: Controls the boot-process of the game.

ObjectManager.name: ObjectManager
ObjectManager.description:
Manages game objects by updating if necessary and offering
methods to add or remove game objects. All game objects are sorted by
the order-property to give control over the update-order.

A game object can registered under a unique ID and then easily accessed using
that ID. If an object gets registered, a global variable $<ID> is created
as well. However, that global variable is only for the use in property-bindings
used for In-Game UI. See ui.Component_BindingHandler.

In addition, a game object can be assigned to a group like for example
a set of UI toggle-buttons can be assigned to the same group and then
easily accessed later using gs.ObjectManager.objectsByGroup method.

Object_Animation.name: Object_Animation
Object_Animation.description: A game object used for animations.

Object_Background.name: Object_Background
Object_Background.description: A game object used for backgrounds in a scene.

Object_Base.name: Object_Base
Object_Base.description:
The base class for all game objects. A game object itself doesn't implement
any game logic but uses components and sub-objects for that.

Object_Character.name: Object_Character
Object_Character.description: A game object for a visual novel character.

Object_CommonEvent.name: Object_CommonEvent
Object_CommonEvent.description:
A common-event object handles a single common event defined in the
database. Common events can run parallel to the actual scene content
or can be just called from a scene to execute a common piece of logic.

Object_Container.name: Object_Container
Object_Container.description: A game object which can contain other game objects.

Object_DataGrid.name: Object_DataGrid
Object_DataGrid.description:
A data-grid allows to display items from a associated data-source using a specified item-template. 
Unlike a stack-layout, a data-grid is optimized to display even high amounts of items but they all
need to use the same item-template with same size.

Object_DomainContainer.name: Object_DomainContainer
Object_DomainContainer.description: A game object which can contain other game objects by domain.

Object_Frame.name: Object_Frame
Object_Frame.description: An UI frame object to display an frame on screen useful for buttons, windows, etc.

Object_FreeLayout.name: Object_FreeLayout
Object_FreeLayout.description:
A free-layout which layouts all sub-objects at their specified positions. 
So that kind of layout allows each sub-object to be freely positioned.

Object_GridLayout.name: Object_GridLayout
Object_GridLayout.description:
A grid-layout which layouts all it sub-objects
in a grid of rows and columns.

Object_Hotspot.name: Object_Hotspot
Object_Hotspot.description:
A hotspot object to define an area on the screen which can respond
to user-actions like mouse/touch actions. A hotspot can have multiple
images for different states like hovered, selected, etc.

Object_Picture.name: Object_Picture
Object_Picture.description: A game object used for pictures in a scene.

Object_ImageMap.name: Object_ImageMap
Object_ImageMap.description: An image-map object to display an image-map on screen.

Object_Image.name: Object_Image
Object_Image.description: An UI image object to display an image on screen.

Object_IntervalTimer.name: Object_IntervalTimer
Object_IntervalTimer.description: A timer object. A timer can be used as a regular timer or as a stop-watch.

Object_Layout.name: Object_Layout
Object_Layout.description:
A layout object defines a new UI layout game scene. A UI layout scene
displays in-game UI and let the user interact with it. For example: The
title screen, the game menu, etc.

Object_Live2DCharacter.name: Object_Live2DCharacter
Object_Live2DCharacter.description: A game object for an animated Live2D visual novel character.

Object_MessageArea.name: Object_MessageArea
Object_MessageArea.description: A game object used for message areas in a scene.

MessageSettings.name: MessageSettings
MessageSettings.description:
Stores the different kind of settings for a message object such as
auto-erase, wait-at-end, backlog writing, etc.

Object_Message.name: Object_Message
Object_Message.description: A message object to display game messages on screen.

Object_Panel.name: Object_Panel
Object_Panel.description:
An UI panel object display a colored rectangle area on screen or can also
be completely transparent. A panel can be modal to block all user-input
for UI object placed behind it. 

So for example: To make a confirmation dialog
like "Do you really want to exit?" a panel is useful to avoid that the user
can click on other UI elements behind the confirmation dialog.

Object_Scene.name: Object_Scene
Object_Scene.description:
A scene object manages a whole visual novel scene with backgrounds, characters,
messages, etc.

Object_SpreadLayout.name: Object_SpreadLayout
Object_SpreadLayout.description:
A spread-layout which spreads all sub-objects evenly over the layout-space 
vertically or horizontally.

Object_StackLayout.name: Object_StackLayout
Object_StackLayout.description:
A stack-layout which layouts all it sub-objects
like a stack vertically or horizontally.

Object_Text.name: Object_Text
Object_Text.description: A game object used for custom texts in a scene.

Object_ThreePartImage.name: Object_ThreePartImage
Object_ThreePartImage.description:
An object to display a three-part image using three
sub-images: start, middle and end. For info, see ui.Component_ThreePartImage.

Object_Timer.name: Object_Timer
Object_Timer.description: A timer object. A timer can be used as a regular timer or as a stop-watch.

Object_UIElement.name: Object_UIElement
Object_UIElement.description: The base class for all In-Game UI objects.

Object_Video.name: Object_Video
Object_Video.description: A game object used for custom texts in a scene.

Object_Viewport.name: Object_Viewport
Object_Viewport.description: A game object used for viewports.

Object_Visual.name: Object_Visual
Object_Visual.description: The base class for all regular visual game objects.

RecordManager.name: RecordManager
RecordManager.description: Manages the game's database and gives access to all data-records.

ResourceLoader.name: ResourceLoader
ResourceLoader.description:
The resource helps to load a bunch of resources from different kind of
data structures.

ResourceManager.name: ResourceManager
ResourceManager.description:
Manages the resources of the game like graphics, audio, fonts, etc. It
offers a lot of methods to easily access game resources and automatically
caches them. So if an image is requested a second time it will be taken
from the cache instead of loading it again.

SceneManager.name: SceneManager
SceneManager.description: Manages the scenes of the game.

Sprite_Debug.name: Sprite_Debug
Sprite_Debug.description: Sprite to display debug information on screen. HINT: Will be probably removed before release.

UIElementPoint.name: UIElementPoint
UIElementPoint.description: An ui point is like a regular point with an x- and y-coordinate but if one of the coordinates is changed the needsUpdate property of the assigned game object will be set to true to trigger a refresh.

UIElementRectangle.name: UIElementRectangle
UIElementRectangle.description: An ui rectangle is like a regular gs.Rect rectangle but if one of the rectangle's coordinates is changed the needsUpdate property of the assigned game object will be set to true to trigger a refresh.

Formula.name: Formula
Formula.description:
Encapsulates a UI formula. A formula can be used in UI layouts to define
property-bindings or to implement a specific behavior.

Space.name: Space
Space.description: Describes a space inside or around something like a margin or padding.

Style.name: Style
Style.description: A UI style can applied to a UI object to modify it properties like color, image, etc. to give a certain "style" to it.

UIManager.name: UIManager
UIManager.description:
Handles the creation of In Game UI elements. For more information about
In-Game UI see help file.

UpdateBehavior.name: UpdateBehavior
UpdateBehavior.description: An enumeration of different UI object update behaviors.

VariableStore.name: VariableStore
VariableStore.description:
A storage for different kind of game variables. The following scopes for variables exist:

- Local Variables -> Only valid for the current scene. - Global Variables -> Valid for the whole game but bound to a single save-game. - Persistent Variables -> Valid for the whole game indepentent from the save-games.

The following data-types exist:

- Strings -> Variables storing text data. - Numbers -> Variables storing integer number values. - Booleans -> Variables storing boolean values. (Called "Switches" for easier understanding) - Lists -> Variables storing multiple other variables. Lists can also contain Lists.

Local variables are stored by scene UID. For each scene UID a list of local variables is stored.

Global and persistent variables are stored and a specific domain. A domain is just a unique name such as com.example.game for example. The default domain is an empty string. Domains are useful to avoid overlapping of variable numbers when sharing content with other users.

This method is called for each token while the message is initialized and also while the message is running. See formattingOnly parameter.
